sentences: Lucas Prata (born December 30, 1968) is an American house musician and DJ from New York City.
Prata was born in Bayside, Queens, New York, in 1978.
In the summer of 2000, Prata joined Salt-n-Pepa as the opening act for their 96-city North American tour, around the time of his hit single "Fly Away".

The track became the 2006 New York Mets anthem, in a parody version, "And We Say...Let's Go Mets", written by David Brody from New York's Elvis Duran and the Morning Show, which Prata performed live at the team's 2006 postseason rally on October 3.

The track became the 2006 New York Mets anthem, in a parody version, "And We Say...Let's Go Mets", written by David Brody from New York's Elvis Duran and the Morning Show, which Prata performed live at the team's 2006 postseason rally on October 3.
The song and its video were regularly played at Shea Stadium during the 2006 season and postseason.
In 2006, while Prata was working as promotions director at Miami's Party 93.1, his single "Let's Get It On" became the #1 requested record at the station.
Prata was the featured performer on an episode of MTV's My Super Sweet Sixteen in 2006.
In 2007, Prata's album Never Stop Dreamin' was licensed by Ministry of Sound in the UK.
It was debuted live on New Year's Eve at Mirage on Long Island, and later performed live at WKTU Beatstock Festival on August 19, 2007.
In 2008, Prata released a remake of "Something About You" by Level 42, a duet with George Lamond.
In 2008 Coca-Cola and the Olympics used "And She Said" as part of their campaign, along with a bottle dedicated to the song and Prata for China.

In his senior year, Prata won the Mr. University of Miami contest.
He subsequently worked as a backing dancer for George LaMond for 10 years.
In the summer of 2000, Prata joined Salt-n-Pepa as the opening act for their 96-city North American tour, around the time of his hit single "Fly Away".
Over the following months, Prata's singles "Never Be Alone", "And She Said", and "Love of My Life" (featuring Reina) all received substantial airplay on radio stations WKTU and WMPH.

The second single from his debut album, "And She Said", had crossover success on the New York City pop station, Z100 where it gained national exposure, holding the #1 dance airplay single spot for four consecutive weeks in Billboard.

The track became the 2006 New York Mets anthem, in a parody version, "And We Say...Let's Go Mets", written by David Brody from New York's Elvis Duran and the Morning Show, which Prata performed live at the team's 2006 postseason rally on October 3.
A Christmas version of the song was also recorded by Prata and released in December.
== 2006-present ==
It was debuted live on New Year's Eve at Mirage on Long Island, and later performed live at WKTU Beatstock Festival on August 19, 2007.
In March 2007 and March 2008, Prata performed with Reina at a benefit event for Muscular Dystrophy hosted by two high schools in Staten Island.
Prata now works as a mentor and consultant for young talent from his home in New Jersey, while continuing to write for other artists.
